1102","8. November 1112":"8 November 1112","1134":"1134","1112":"1112","1057":"1057","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","1111":"1111","1199":"1199","Budenheim, Mainz-Bingen, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Budenheim, Mainz-Bingen, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland":"Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland","Habsburg, Aargau, Schweiz":"Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland","Monte Porzio, Roma, Lazio, Italia":"Monte Porzio Catone, Roma, Lazio, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graf","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Erwin, Ernst, Fritz, Gerhard, Hermann, Horst, Manfred, Udo, Alois.","German (also <b>Gräf</b>): status name from Middle High German <i>grāve</i>, <i>grābe</i>, which was used as a title denoting various more or less aristocratic dignitaries and officials. In later times it became established as a title of nobility equivalent to the Romance count. The vocabulary word also denoted a variety of different minor local functionaries in different parts of Germany. In the Grand Duchy of Hesse, for example, it was used for the holder of the comparatively humble office of village headman (compare   Mayer  ,   Schulz  , and   Vogt  ). The surname could have originated from any of these senses or be a metonymic occupational or status name for a servant or retainer of a count, or a nickname for someone who gave himself airs and graces. This surname is also found in many other European countries, for example in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Hungary, Poland, Czechia, Slovakia, Croatia, and Slovenia, often as a translation into German of the corresponding Hungarian and Slavic surnames <b>Gróf</b> and   Grof  . Compare   Graef  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name selected, like   Herzog   and other words denoting titles, because of their aristocratic connotations."],"variants":[{"name":"Grebe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Erwin, Fritz, Hans, Willi.","German (Hesse): variant of   Graf  ."]},{"name":"De Graaf","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Dutch Gerrit, Adriaan, Bastiaan, Cornelis, Dirk, Geert.","Dutch: from <i>graaf</i> ‘count’ (see   Graf  ), with the addition of the definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, hence a nickname for the servant of a count or for someone supposedly resembling one, and also a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn named with this word."]},{"name":"Graefe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Arno, Goetz, Horst, Johannes.","German (North Rhine-Westphalia; also <b>Gräfe</b>): variant of   Graf   1."]},{"name":"Grefe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erhardt, Gerhard, Gerhart, Kurt.","North German: variant of   Graf  ."]},{"name":"Greve","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Otto, Reinhold, Bernhardt, Claus, Erna, Erwin, Ewald, Fritz, Kurt.","North German and Scandinavian: status name from Middle Low German and Danish <i>greve</i> ‘count’, equivalent to German   Graf  .","Dutch: vowel variant of   Grave   ‘count’, or a topographic name from Middle Dutch <i>greve</i> ‘ditch, moat, channel’."]},{"name":"Croff","meanings":["Altered form of German   Graf   or   Graff  . Or of Dutch   Kroft  ."]},{"name":"Mayer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Franz, Helmut, Wilhelm, Erwin, Gerhard, Heinz, Ilse, Lorenz, Wolfgang.","English (Staffordshire): post-medieval form of <b>Mear</b>, which is either a topographic name, from Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘pond, pool’ (Old English <i>mere</i>) or Middle English <i>mere</i> ‘boundary’ (Old English <i>(ge)mǣre</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places with names derived from these terms, such as Mere (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Wiltshire), Meir in Caverswall (Staffordshire), and Meare (Somerset).","English: occupational name for a physician, from Old French <i>mire</i>, Middle English <i>mire</i>, <i>meir</i>, <i>meyre</i>, originally synonymous with   Myer  ."]},{"name":"Grafe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Fritz, Ralf.","German (also <b>Gräfe</b>): variant of   Graf   1."]},{"name":"Graef","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Egon, Lothar, Otto, Armin, Claus, Erwin, Franz, Friedrich, Hans, Helmut, Hermann, Jochen.","German (also <b>Gräf</b>): see   Graf  .","Dutch: variant of <b>Graaf</b>, see   De Graaf  ."]},{"name":"Graff","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (also <b>Gräff</b>): variant of   Graf  . Compare   Graeff  .","English (London): metonymic occupational name for a clerk or scribe, from Old French <i>grafe</i> ‘stylus, pencil’, a derivative of Old French <i>grafer</i> ‘to write’ (from Late Latin <i>grafare</i>, from Greek <i>graphein</i>). It is uncertain whether the English name survived the medieval period or whether the early 17th century bearers in Britain were in fact of German origin."]}]},{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Werner","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from the tribal name <i>Warin</i> + <i>heri</i> ‘army’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wernher","meanings":["from the tribal name <i>Warin</i> + <i>heri</i> ‘army’."]}]},{"name":"II.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Werner II. Graf von Habsburg was born in 1102, in Habsburg, Aargau, Switzerland, his father, Otto II. Graf von Habsburg, was 45 and his mother, Hilda bzw. Ita von Pfirt bzw. Ferrette, was 17. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Ida von Homberg. He died on 19 August 1167, in Monte Porzio Catone, Roma, Lazio, Italy, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1102–19. August 1167":"1102–19. august 1167","1092–1134":"1092–1134","1102–1167":"1102–1167","1110–1200":"1110–1200","1138–1199":"1138–1199","–Female":"Surnud","1057–1112":"1057–1112","1085–1134":"1085–1134","about 1091":"umbes 1091","1110":"1110","19. August 1167":"19. august 1167","1085":"1085","1092":"1092","1138":"1138","1102":"1102","8. November 1112":"8. novem